<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFB5FFEF6DC2FC47FC5AAF0C" pageId="17" pageNumber="1530" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFB5FFEF6DC2FC47FC5AAF0C" blockId="17.[178,1085,986,1038]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1530">
Etymology: The specific epithet 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB5FFEF6F29FC47FD2EA8ED" box="[601,699,986,1007]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1530">alarutinis</emphasis>
is a Latin compound name derived from 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB5FFEF6D99FC65FE9CAF0F" box="[233,265,1016,1037]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1530">ala</emphasis>
(= wing) and 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB5FFEF6CEAFC65FE49AF0F" box="[410,476,1016,1037]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1530">rutilus</emphasis>
(= red). I refer to the red coloration of the elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
